window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2004>1>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2004","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"SIMPLE HARMONIC MOTION : PERIOD, FREQUENCY AND AMPLITUDE OF A BODY EXECUTING S.H.M","question":"You have been provided with a retort stand, clamp and boss; metre rule; a spiral spring; a set of slotted weights and a pointer.  (i) Set up the apparatus as shown in the diagram above.  (ii) Read and record the length,  l o, of the spiral spring.  (iii) Place a mass of m = 50.0 g on the hanger.  (iv) Read and record the new length,  l , of the spring.  (v) Determine the extension e =  l  -  l o.  (vi) Set the system into small vertical oscillations. Measure and record the time t for ten complete oscillations.  (vii) Determine the period, T, of the oscillations and evaluate T2.  (viii) Repeat the procedure for four other values of m = 100.0, 150.0, 200.0, and 250.0 g. Tabulate your readings.  (ix) Plot a graph of e on the vertical axis against T2 on the horizontal axis.  (x) Determine the slope, s, of the graph.  (xi) Evaluate b = 4&#960;2 &#215; s.  (xii) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate results.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"l o = 37.20 cm    S/Nm(g) l (cm)e =  l o -  l  (cm)t(s)T=t10\\frac{t}{10}10t\u200b(s)T2(s2)150.0039.802.603.200.3200.102100.0040.903.703.750.3750.143150.0042.004.804.980.4980.254200.0043.105.905.510.5510.305250.0044.207.006.020.6020.36        s = y2\u2212y1x2\u2212x1\\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}x2\u200b\u2212x1\u200by2\u200b\u2212y1\u200b\u200b = 6.5\u221230.34\u22120.12\\frac{6.5-3}{0.34-0.12}0.34\u22120.126.5\u22123\u200b = 17511\\frac{175}{11}11175\u200b = 15.91 cm/s2    b = 4&#960;2 \u00d7 s = 4 \u00d7 (227\\frac{22}{7}722\u200b)2 \u00d7 15.91 = 628.61 cm/s2 = 6.29 m/s2    Precautions:  1. I carefully avoided parallax error by aligning my eye perpendicularly with the markings on the meter rule to ensure accurate readings.  2. I accounted for any zero error on the timing device and adjusted my measurements accordingly to obtain precise values for the period of oscillation.  3. I repeated each measurement multiple times and took an average to reduce random errors and improve accuracy.  4. I ensured that the setup was stable and free of external disturbances to maintain consistency in the oscillations and prevent inaccurate measurements.  5. I used properly calibrated instruments to minimize instrumental errors and checked for any wear or damage that could affect readings.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2004>1>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2004","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"HOOKE\u2019S LAW, YOUNG\u2019S MODULES AND WORK DONE IN SPRINGS AND STRING :","question":"State  Hooke's Law  for an elastic material.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Hooke's Law states that, for an elastic material, the force applied to stretch or compress the material is directly proportional to the resulting extension or compression, provided the material's elastic limit is not exceeded. Mathematically, it is expressed as:  F = kx  where   F is the applied force,   k is the material's spring constant (a measure of its stiffness), and   x is the displacement from its original length.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2004>1>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2004","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"HOOKE\u2019S LAW, YOUNG\u2019S MODULES AND WORK DONE IN SPRINGS AND STRING :","question":"A spiral spring is compressed by 0.03 m. Calculate the energy stored in the spring if its force constant is 300 Nm-1.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The energy stored in a spiral spring is given as:    W = 12\\frac{1}{2}21\u200bkx2 = 12\\frac{1}{2}21\u200b \u00d7 300 \u00d7 0.032 = 0.135 J","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2004>2>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2004","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT CURVED SURFACES","question":"You are provided with a converging lens, a plane mirror, a ray box, a screen and a metre rule.  (i) Mount the plane mirror behind the lens and place the ray box until a sharp image of the cross wire is obtained in front of the box, beside the cross wire.  (ii) Adjust the position of the ray box until a sharp image of the cross wire is obtained in front of the box, beside the cross wire.  (iii) Measure and record the distance of the cross wire from the lens. This position of the cross wire is F1.  (iv) Repeat the procedure with the lens reversed to obtain F2.  (v) Replace the mirror with a screen.  (vi) Move the ray box a distance d = 10.0 cm from F2 and adjust the position of the screen beyond F1 until a sharp image of the wire is formed on the screen as shown in diagram II.  (vii) Measure and record the distance,  l  between F1 and the screen. Evaluate  l -1.  (viii) Repeat procedure (v), (vi) and (vii) for four other values d = 15.0, 20.0, 25.0 and 30.0 cm. Tabulate your readings.  (ix) Plot a graph of  l -1 on the vertical axis against d on the horizontal axis.  (x) Determine the slope, s of the graph.  (xi) Evaluate 1(s)\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{\\left(s\\right)}}(s)\u200b1\u200b.  (xii) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate results.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"S/Nd(cm) l (cm) l -1(cm-1)110.0022.500.04215.0015.000.07320.0011.250.09425.009.000.11530.007.500.13        s = y2\u2212y1x2\u2212x1\\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}x2\u200b\u2212x1\u200by2\u200b\u2212y1\u200b\u200b = 0.13\u22120.0430\u221210\\frac{0.13-0.04}{30-10}30\u2212100.13\u22120.04\u200b = 92000\\frac{9}{2000}20009\u200b = 0.0045 cm-2    1(s)\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{\\left(s\\right)}}(s)\u200b1\u200b = 1(92000)\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{\\left(\\frac{9}{2000}\\right)}}(20009\u200b)\u200b1\u200b = 14.91 cm    Precautions:  1. I carefully avoided parallax error by aligning my eye directly perpendicular to the markings on the meter rule to ensure precise readings.  2. I adjusted the setup to ensure a sharp and focused image formed on the screen, confirming that the image quality was optimal before recording measurements.  3. I stabilized all equipment to prevent any vibrations or movements that could disturb the alignment and clarity of the image.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2004>2>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2004","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT CURVED SURFACES","question":"Define the  principal focus  of a converging lens.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The principal focus of a converging lens is the point on the optical axis where rays of light that enter the lens parallel to the axis converge after passing through the lens. This point is located on the opposite side of the lens from the incoming light and helps determine the lens's focal length.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2004>2>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2004","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT CURVED SURFACES","question":"An object and its real image are located at distances 25.0 cm and 40.0 cm from the two principal foci of a converging lens respectively. Calculate the focal length of the lens.    (Provide your answer to 2 d.p and with the unit e.g 12.12 g)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"1f\\frac{1}{f}f1\u200b = 1u\\frac{1}{u}u1\u200b + 1v\\frac{1}{v}v1\u200b    1f\\frac{1}{f}f1\u200b = 125\\frac{1}{25}251\u200b + 140\\frac{1}{40}401\u200b    1f\\frac{1}{f}f1\u200b = 13200\\frac{13}{200}20013\u200b    f = 20013\\frac{200}{13}13200\u200b    \u2234 f = 15.38 cm","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2004>3>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2004","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CURRENT ELECTRICITY","question":"You have been provided with a resistance box, a voltmeter, a key and a battery.  (i) Connect the circuit as shown un the diagram above.  (ii) With the key, K closed, read and record the voltmeter reading Vo.  (iii) Set the resistance R in the resistance box equal to 1 \u03a9. Close the key, read and record the potential difference V on the voltmeter. Evaluate R-1 and V-1.  (iv) Repeat the procedure for five other values of R = 2, 3, 4, 5 and 6 \u03a9. Tabulate your readings.  (v) Plot a graph of V-1 on the vertical axis against R-1 on the horizontal axis.  (vi) Determine the slope of graph and the intercept I on the vertical axis.  (vii) Evaluate I-1.  (viii) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate results.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Voltmeter reading, E = 2.0 V     S/NR(\u03a9)R-1(\u03a9-1)V(V)V-1(V-1)11.001.001.800.5622.000.502.100.4833.000.332.300.4344.000.252.400.4255.000.202.500.4066.000.172.600.38        (vi) Slope = y2\u2212y1x2\u2212x1\\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}x2\u200b\u2212x1\u200by2\u200b\u2212y1\u200b\u200b = 0.55\u22120.40.9\u22120.2\\frac{0.55-0.4}{0.9-0.2}0.9\u22120.20.55\u22120.4\u200b = 314\\frac{3}{14}143\u200b = 0.21 \u03a9/V    (vi) I = 0.36 V-1    (vii) I-1 = 0.36-1 = 10.36\\frac{1}{0.36}0.361\u200b = 2.78 V    (viii) Precautions:  1. I ensured that all connecting wires were tightly and securely connected to minimize resistance and prevent any energy loss or loose connections that could impact the readings.  2. I carefully avoided parallax error by positioning my eye directly in front of the voltmeter scale when taking readings to ensure accuracy.  3. I inspected the apparatus for any loose or damaged connections before starting the experiment to prevent errors due to faulty equipment.  4. I used a calibrated voltmeter and verified it was in good working condition to avoid instrumental errors.  5. I minimized external interference by keeping the setup stable and free from movement that could impact the connections or affect the readings.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2004>3>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2004","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : POTENTIAL DIFFERENCE AND ELECTRIC CURRENT","question":"Define  potential difference  between two points in an electric circuit.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The potential difference between two points in an electric circuit is the amount of work done per unit charge to move a charge from one point to the other. It represents the energy difference available to drive electric current between those two points and is measured in volts (V).","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2004>3>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2004","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CURRENT, POTENTIAL DIFFERENCE, RESISTANCE, E.M.F. AND INTERNAL RESISTANCE","question":"Explain why the emf of a cell is greater than the p.d across the cell when it is supplying current through an external resistance.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The electromotive force (emf) of a cell is greater than the potential difference (p.d.) across the cell when it is supplying current due to the internal resistance of the cell. When current flows, some energy is lost as heat within the cell due to this internal resistance. As a result, the voltage measured across the terminals of the cell (the p.d.) is lower than the emf, which represents the total energy supplied by the cell per unit charge without any load.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"}];